messages.message: Uploaded patch set 1.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2 Sanity-Review+1

Apparently pushing a Work In Progress

Patch Set 1:

Imo, if you want to introduce this, it should be a *new* plugin, that should be renamed, and be called appropriately (so maplibre or something, hence renaming its directory etc).
As i wrote earlier, imo it would be better, in particular for maplibre folks and for those using such a plugin, to include this plugin into their codebase rather than here.
This would give a lot more freedom in adding features and having a more appropriate release schedule compared to it being part of Qt and having to follow Qt release schedule.
This, in addition to the submodule itself, that is a whole different story.
Right now mapbox-gl-native repo is mirrored at git.qt.io.
I doubt the same will be done with maplibre, and therefore a part of Qt that depends on an external git repo that might disappear at any time thus making it unbuildable does not seem the best approach

just my 2c

Patch Set 1:

Yes, I thought about it myself but for the sake of small diff and easy change tracking, I would like to get it working first. And when it works, we can decide further action. It would be very appriciates if someone could help me understand why it doesn't render anything on screen. My learning curve in this graphics field is a bit steep.

How will this react when the user passes `&QLineEdit::destroyed, &lineEdit`? How should it?

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> How will this react when the user passes `&QLineEdit::destroyed, &lineEdit`? How should it?

Sorry, what are those parameters?  Signal+receiver?

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> > Patch Set 2:
> > 
> > How will this react when the user passes `&QLineEdit::destroyed, &lineEdit`? How should it?
> 
> Sorry, what are those parameters?  Signal+receiver?

The *signal* parameters are not the issue. Only the slot.

Let's say you wrote &lineEdit, &QLineEdit::update. The second parameter is just a nice way of writing &QWidget::update, so Obj=QWidget. If the object pointer is passed while the object is still a QLineEdit or QWidget, the assertion will be quiet. If the QWidget destruction has finished and the object is a QObject, the assertion shall fail.

I guess we can make it a qWarning(), but technically, the following UB will allow the compiler to completely remove the warning, so at the least we should have a unit test that checks that the warning is, indeed, emitted.

Patch Set 9:

> Patch Set 9:
> 
> With this change, Qt Quick tests start asserting. The assert fires for this example, which I think is close to what we see in Qt Quick.
> 
> Until we have figured this out, I vote for a revert of this change lest we block qtdeclarative dependency updates for a potentially long time. I understand the problem, but I don't think this is the right solution.

The test was wrong anyhow; running it under e.g. UBSAN would've caused an error. Yes, we need sanitizer coverage, long story... 

A "better" solution would be to avoid invoking the slot entirely rather than asserting (à la SIGNAL/SLOT-based overload), but AFAIU, that's not for free: it's going to involve a qobject_cast/dynamic_cast call per emission, that however everyone is going to pay for -- and normally that's not needed, in the sense that ~100% of the time an activation doesn't involve objects that are being destroyed. (I personally wouldn't mind, as the cost of a qobject_cast isn't "crazy" expensive -- esp. compared with a virtual call, again as what happens for the SIGNAL/SLOT overloads -- but I get the point)

Patch Set 9:

Patch Set 9:

> Patch Set 9:
> 
> The test is UB. Fix the test. Once the test no longer has UB, we can talk.

The test is not UB, Qt very clearly promises that it takes care of connections when the sender or receiver are destroyed. The test relies on this promise, as does at least some code in Qt (evidently), and quite probably plenty of user code out there.

Qt calling the slot function on an object that is being destroyed is UB. But replacing UB with an assert doesn't really help, given that the code is valid Qt usage. The receiver code shouldn't have to care about when the signal gets emitted; enabling this kind of loose coupling is the *core* promise of the signal/slot mechanism.

So, I'm questing the assert, not that the problem exists. I don't have a perfect solution; we can always skip the slot-call, perhaps with a qWarning, which means we always have to try the qobject_cast for each signal emission.

Patch Set 9:

We're all agreed that this commit's parent has UB in this case. We're also agreed that the old-style connect nicely avoids the UB, more or less by design.

Volker's point, CMIImW, is that this was a feature of the old-style connect, one that people came to rely upon (Hyrum's Law again) and that a simple port from old-style connect to the new - recommended - new-style connect syntax breaks unearths UB. In this light, the bug is not in the example, because it works with old-style-connect, and therefore is using 30yr-old established practice, but that Qt is buggy by not implementing the same feature for new-style-connect.

I feel persuaded, actually.

The question then becomes: how do we get that feature into new-style-connect in an efficient manner?

Patch Set 9:

This is the one difference in behaviour we've documented between old and new style connects. It's also not new: it's been there since the feature was deployed. People for whom it crashed when porting have long since fixed the problem in their codebases.

The problem is the cases where the UB just happened to produce no ill-effects: calling a PMF that didn't depend on any already-destroyed value (or the already-destroyed values didn't cause further misbehaviour). This is what this commit is now telling you: your code is bad and you have a ticking time-bomb. Fix it.

Because most people who were affected have already fixed the problem and the vast majority of signal-slot deliveries are not affected by the destruction-in-progress case, I am opposed to adding extra code here.

It wouldn't be too difficult: the very same dynamic_cast or qobject_cast can be used to determine to the parent frame whether to invoke the PMF or not. Another solution would be to make this stateful and store the current metaobject or typeinfo, then bypass the inheritance check if that hasn't changed since the last time we've checked. Adding an extra pointer to QSlotObject is not trivial (would probably involve a QSlotObjectBaseV2), but it is possible.

Patch Set 9:

Thinking out loud, I think we'd need to profile carefully the cost of the unconditional cast. dynamic_cast can be expensive, but how much is it in practice (considering the stringent single-inheritance line from QObject)? What about qobject_cast? And what about old-style connect?

Only some numbers could give us the confidence that we can "upgrade" the assert to an unconditional test.

Patch Set 9:

> Patch Set 9:
> 
> Thinking out loud, I think we'd need to profile carefully the cost of the unconditional cast. dynamic_cast can be expensive, but how much is it in practice (considering the stringent single-inheritance line from QObject)? What about qobject_cast? And what about old-style connect?

QObject is a __class_type_info, so its dynamic_cast ends up here:
https://code.woboq.org/gcc/libstdc++-v3/libsupc++/class_type_info.cc.html#__cxxabiv1::__class_type_info::__do_dyncast

However, all descendants from QObject are, by necessity, at least __si_class_type_info, so https://code.woboq.org/gcc/libstdc++-v3/libsupc++/si_class_type_info.cc.html#__cxxabiv1::__si_class_type_info::__do_dyncast. The vmi typeinfo is even more complex, but the majority of classes won't be that.

The implementation inside libstdc++, as you can see, is doing a virtual call through the typeinfo inheritance. That's always an indirect call, though likely warm cache because it's calling back to itself. The libc++ implementation looks more complex, but ends up doing the same: https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/blob/main/libcxxabi/src/private_typeinfo.cpp#L1036

The qobject_cast, on the other hand, makes a single virtual call, to obtain the current meta object. After that, QMetaObject::inherits() simply does a pointer-chasing across the meta object hierarchy. It cannot be worse than the dynamic_cast.

As for the string-based connection, there is no check. The difference is in delivery, because it uses the virtual qt_metacall(). Unfortunately, the cost of that is equivalent to the cost of indirect pointer call to QSlotObject::impl.

> Only some numbers could give us the confidence that we can "upgrade" the assert to an unconditional test.

Instead of creating a new topic, consider using the current "Connecting Android Devices" topic: https://doc.qt.io/qtcreator/creator-developing-android.html

Making that topic visible in the QDS Manual and modifying it by using conditional text, as appropriate, would reduce the maintenance burden when the Android settings change in Qt Creator 7.0 (there are already some user-visible changes in the master branch: https://bugreports.qt.io/browse/QTCREATORBUG-26672).

> +1 for describing how to use Android Studio for the initial Android SDK setup. I believe this is the least troublesome option (and I suggest 1st-time Qt Android users to try this first), and wished this was also in the Qt Creator docs.

I'm not against adding that information to the Qt Creator Manual, too, even though describing 3rd party apps is tricky, so I'd like us to specifically mention which Android Studio version we are using as an example. So, that's another vote for just modifying the original topic.

Patch Set 1:

I wouldn't be able to tell the conceptual difference between IDeviceFactory::setDisplayPlatform and setDisplayName.

Do we really need both? 

If the 'Device' suffix is 'a problem', would just dropping it be an option?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> I wouldn't be able to tell the conceptual difference between IDeviceFactory::setDisplayPlatform and setDisplayName.
> 
> Do we really need both? 
> 
> If the 'Device' suffix is 'a problem', would just dropping it be an option?

We might not need to both, but from what I see, this string is used in different places in different contexts, for example one referring to the device type in kits settings, and another referring to the platform in new project wizard. A more simpler way is to remove "Device" suffix from the name when used as a "platform name", but was an attempt to make it more explicit and not manipulate the string, but it creates the burden of having to set another value from each platform plugin.
Removed reviewer Eike Ziller.

I'd try to get away with only one such string, even if this means some messages will change or need adaptation. 

My best guess is that a version without 'device' would do, if the 'device' part needs to be stressed that could be done in the surrounding text of the message ( tr("The device \"%1\").arg(...))
